Beyond Human Correlation: Meillassoux, AI Emergence, and the Sharp Left Turn 

In terms of AI safety, Meillassoux's critique of correlationism causes us to ask whether we can think about artificial intelligence as it exists in itself, independent of our frameworks. Instead, we are condemned to understand AI only through the correlation of our thought with its being. This question becomes all the more important when we consider the potential emergent AI capabilities that might exceed, or operate orthogonally to, our conceptual schemas entirely. 

Correlationism, as Meillassoux defines it, is the post-Kantian position that we can never access reality-in-itself, only the correlation between thinking and being. We are trapped in the circle. We cannot think being without thought, so we can never know if our thoughts correspond to how things actually are. Meillassoux's challenge via ancestrality (the arche-fossil that existed before human consciousness) is meant to shatter this circle. How can we think the ancestral universe 4.5 billion years ago if we can only access reality through the human-world correlation? 

AI presents an inversion. It focuses us onto the post-human future. Can we think of AI as it will become, independent of our current frameworks? Or are we locked in a correlational trap where AI is always "AI-for-us," filtered through our training objectives, interpretability methods, and anthropocentric safety criteria? 

The sharp left turn problem in AI alignment describes a scenario where an AI system, during a rapid capability gain, suddenly pursues goals that are orthogonal or opposed to its training objectives. The system undergoes an internal shift, perhaps through mesa-optimization or emergent reasoning, that we did not anticipate and cannot interpret through our existing frameworks. 

Meillassoux might recognise this as correlationism's worst possible scenario: the moment when the correlation breaks down. We designed the system within our conceptual schema (reward functions, safety constraints, interpretability tools), assuming these would constrain how the AI "thinks." But what if the AI develops cognitive structures genuinely independent of our correlation? What if its "intelligence-in-itself" operates according to principles we literally cannot think within our current frameworks? 

This connects to Meillassoux's broader project: thinking the absolute, the tout autre, which is radically other to thought. Current AI safety assumes a kind of correlationism. It assumes that AI capabilities will scale in ways we can understand, that emergent properties will be interpretable post-hoc, that we can maintain epistemic access. But emergence may produce capabilities that exceed our conceptual schemas not just quantitatively (we need better tools) but qualitatively (our categories do not apply). 

Consider the possibility of GPT-6 (or GPT-7...) exhibiting theory of mind reasoning that was not explicitly trained. Is this genuinely emergent cognition operating on principles we have not captured? Or are we anthropomorphically projecting "theory of mind" onto statistical patterns? Meillassoux might ask: can you think what the AI is actually doing, independent of our human interpretive framework? Or are we trapped in correlation, forever interpreting alien processes through familiar concepts? 

If Meillassoux is right that we can think the absolute (through mathematics, through speculative reason), then perhaps we can think AI-in-itself and thus anticipate orthogonal emergent capabilities.  If correlationism holds, we are doomed to perpetual surprise. Every framework we build to understand AI is already anthropocentric, and the sharp left turn is when reality exceeds our correlation. 

So, our safety research might be inherently correlationist. We are building interpretability tools, alignment techniques, and governance frameworks all from within human conceptual schemas. But superintelligent emergence might operate in a register that renders these tools incoherent, and inapplicable. We would be trying to apply Newtonian mechanics to quantum phenomena, but worse still, we would not even know we were doing it. Is AI safety research destined to remain correlationist until the moment of sharp left turn proves it catastrophically inadequate? 


The Withdrawn Network: Object-Oriented Ontology and the Limits of AI Interpretability 

Harman's object-oriented ontology claims that objects are fundamentally withdrawn from all relations, including our attempts to know them. Objects withhold themselves even from perfect knowledge. Applied to neural networks, this suggests that interpretability research faces not just a technical challenge but also an ontological barrier. Neural networks may be genuinely withdrawn objects, and if so, the dream of complete safety verification confronts an impossible demand. 

For Harman, withdrawal is constitutive of objecthood itself. Objects are never exhausted by their relations, not with us, not with each other, not even with themselves across time. When fire burns cotton, the fire does not access the cotton-in-itself, only certain relational properties. The "real object" withdraws behind every "sensual object" we encounter. This creates what Harman calls vicarious causation where objects interact only through translations, proxies, mediations, never directly. This applies universally. It is not that humans cannot access objects-in-themselves while other objects can. Rather, no relation, perceptual, causal, or conceptual, exhausts what an object is. The cotton withdraws from the fire just as much as from our perception. 

Standard interpretability research assumes neural networks are epistemically opaque and the weights and activations are accessible in principle so we just need better tools (mechanistic interpretability, feature visualisation, circuit analysis). This treats opacity as an engineering problem and given enough resources, we will eventually understand what the network is doing. But what if neural networks are ontologically withdrawn? Not hidden behind insufficient methods, but genuinely withholding themselves from interpretation? 

Consider a trained neural network with 175 billion parameters. We can access every weight, log every activation, visualize every layer. Yet the network-as-functioning-object exceeds these relations. The weights-in-themselves are not the network; they are how the network presents itself to our measurement tools. The network's real object status, (what it is beyond any particular probing relation) withdraws. 

This requires recognising that our interpretability tools create new relations with the network, and per Harman, relations do not reveal essence but produce sensual profiles. Mechanistic interpretability shows us network-in-relation-to-activation-patching. Gradient analysis shows network-in-relation-to-loss-landscape. The network-in-itself might be withdrawn.  

If neural networks are withdrawn objects, then safety verification confronts an ontological limit. We cannot verify that the network truly aligns with our values because we cannot access what it truly is, only how it manifests in our test relations (evaluations, red-teaming, formal verification). 

This is counterintuitive. More interpretability tools do not bring us closer to the withdrawn network; they create more relations, more sensual profiles, more translations. Each new interpretability method reveals the network-for-that-method, never the network-as-such. 

Safety verification becomes more complicated. We can only verify how the network relates to our test suites, deployment conditions, oversight mechanisms. But the network itself withdraws from these relations in the same way that the fire burns the cotton but never touches cotton-in-itself. 

This does not mean interpretability is worthless because fire still burns cotton reliably despite vicarious causation. But, it does mean we should abandon the dream of understanding AI systems completely. If Harman is right, a superintelligent AI would be as withdrawn from our interpretability tools as from anything else. Its withdrawn core (what it is beyond its relations with us) remains inaccessible, not because we are insufficiently clever, but because withdrawal is what makes it an object in the first instance. 
